@endnode
@node "CMD_LHyperGuide" "Command: @HyperGuide"
@toc "Commands"

 @{MS "Command: \@HyperGuide"}

This command is only checked if present. If it is missing or not at the beginning, then nothing
happends.@{par}

I think this is not so hard, because if someone is not able to write this line, then this person is
not able to write a whole guide. (-8@{par}

@endnode
@node "CMD_LMacro" "Command: @Macro"
@toc "Commands"

 @{MS "Command: \@Macro"}

The \@Macro-Command is very complex. It is possible to specify arguments and it is possible, when
using @{"HTDS" link "PT_HTDS"}, to nest macros.@{par}

Let`s take this macro:@{par}

\@macro "Test" "lindent $1"@{par}

GuideCheck isn`t checking if the specified argument is a number. (\@indent expects a number). I
don't think that I'll implement this.@{par}

Only the number of arguments will be counted, so the macro above requires exact one argument:@{par}

\@{test 4}@{par}

As you can see, the macro is not very useful. (-8@{par}

@{b}HTDS@{ub}@{par}

@{"HTDS" link "PT_HTDS"} allows to nest macros. I don't use HDTS and GuideCheck is an AmigaGuide
checking tool, so this feature is implemented, but there are some restrictions:@{par}

A Macro must be defined just @{b}before@{ub} it is used. HTDS is scanning the whole text for macros
without any checking. In addition to that the command @{"@include" link "CMD_LInclude"} is not
working 100%, so external macros aren't present. But you are able to insert them at front of your
guide file.@{par}

@endnode
@node "CMD_LInclude" "Command: @Include"
@toc "Commands"

 @{MS "Command: \@Include"}

The \@include command is a HTDS command and is not really supported. GuideCheck is checking the syntax
of this command, but there is no checking of the specified file.

@endnode

@node "FAQS" "Frequently ask Questions"
@toc "MAIN"

 @{MS "Frequently ask Questions"}

AmigaGuide specific:@{par}

@{"My EMAIL address is reported as an error. Why?" link "FAQSEMAIL"}@{par}

@{"Links to other Amiga guide files are causing errors. Why?" link "FAQSFLINK"}

@endnode
@node "FAQSEMAIL" "FAQ: My EMAIL address is reported as an error. Why?"
@toc "FAQS"

 @{MS "My EMAIL address is reported as an error. Why?"}

The EMail problem is very easy to explain. GuideCheck is checking "\@" as AmigaGuide command
sequence and your EMail address is not a valid command.@{par}

It is not allowed to use a "\@" within an AmigaGuide. Depending on the Version of the
amigaguide.library this may cause various problems.@{par}

You are allowed to use a "\@", like I just did, by using a "\\" right before the "\@"! When you are
viewing the guide it looks like "\@", but if you use a normal text editor it looks like "\\\@"!. The
backslash allows to insert characters that are normally not available or are used by the Amigaguide
parser itself.@{par}

A backslash itself can be used in the same way: "\\\\"!@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSFLINK" "FAQ: Links to other Amiga guide files are causing errors. Why?"
@toc "FAQS"

 @{MS "Links to other Amiga guide files are causing errors. Why?"}

I think you are not using the Kickstart 3.1 version of the AmigaGuide datatype.@{par}

Some older versions allow special definitions of links into other guide files. These definitions
aren't working with the newest version.@{par}

Like many times before! It`s there. It`s working. It`s not allowed. It`s used.@{par}

As Commodore said: "Everything that's not allowed, even if it is now working, won`t work in the
future."@{par}

\@{"Link to other file" link "File2/Main"}@{par}

@{b}This is the only correct way. It`s not allowed to remove the "/Main", even if it is working on
your system.@{ub}@{par}

@endnode

